    "comment": "Rationale: \"The lipid transfer protein ORP2 is a cytosolic protein belonging to the family of oxysterol-binding proteins/OSBP-related proteins (ORPs).\"\n\nFigure 1a: Immunofluorescence imaging of endogenous ORP2, vGlut1 and MAP2 in autaptic hippocampal neurons from mice confirmed presynaptic localization for ORP2 (gene OSBPL2).\n\nFigure 1b: ORP2 co-immunoprecipitated with Stx1A, SNAP-25, and VAPA in hippocampal neurons.\n\nFigure 1c: Immunofluorescence imaging of autaptic hippocampal neurons transduced with proteins tagged for bimolecular fluorescence complementation (BiFC) interaction showed synaptic interaction of ORP2 with syntaxin1a (STX1A) and SNAP25.\n\nFigure 3: The cholesterol transport function of ORP2 is essential for Ca2+-evoked neurotransmitter release and STP in hippocampal neurons.. Experimental description: M&M: \"Primary hippocampal neurons were obtained from P0-P2 newborn mice (of either sex) and cultured on 1-3-week-old astrocyte feeding layers.\"\n\nantibody:\nRabbit anti-ORP2, Laitinen et al.,(20) PMID:11861666\nRabbit anti-ORP2, Abcam, Cat# 96530; RRID:AB_10680375\ngene nomenclature; abcam antibody links to NCBI GenBank accession NP_055650 (gene OSBPL2)",
